}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af1 \ltrch\fcs0 \f1\insrsid8197677 Housework}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af1 \ltrch\fcs0 \f1\insrsid14184279\charrsid16072257 
\par Geographic region}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af1 \ltrch\fcs0 \f1\insrsid14184279 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af1 \ltrch\fcs0 \f1\insrsid14184279\charrsid16072257 :}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af1 \ltrch\fcs0 \f1\insrsid14184279  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af1 \ltrch\fcs0 \f1\insrsid8197677 
Isle of Lewis}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af1 \ltrch\fcs0 \f1\insrsid14184279\charrsid16072257 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-461\li461\ri0\sa240\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin461\itap0\pararsid14184279 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Could you tell me what part of the island you come from?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Well I was brought up in a place cal
led Shairbosir on the West coast of Lewis. I was there until I was about thirteen years. And then our family removed to Stornaway. We lived there, and I - spent my schooldays - my secondary school - days in Stornaway. Stornaway at that time of course was 
quite different to what it is today. We didn't have as many outsiders in Stornaway, it has completely changed. And - then after I - do you want my whole life?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Could you tell me the year that you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Well have I got to disclose my age?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Very roughly.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 
The beginning of the century. 1901 to be exact. And - I attended the Shawbost school, which at that time of course was quite big, at least the role because - it was - and it was just the - village children, today it's different. And th
ey haven't got the same number on the board - as they had then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 It was a board school was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Boys and girls?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Oh yes. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Can you tell me something about the teachers there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Well they weren't local teachers in t
hose days, there were very few who could teach, they were all - from - different - well, from the mainland. And - the headmaster of course - it - it changed during my time, and - it was a local gentleman who became headmaster, when I left school I'd just 
had a year of him. And - well in those days of course - the housing was different. People got very comfortable in their - streamlined black houses.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 What kind of a house did your own family have?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Well we had a stone house. As father was a - baker 
in the village, and - in in those days of course - you - his business didn't flourish because of the lack of money. And - when the war broke out - he was - he - he got - well from his former employer - to go to Stornaway and take out there. So -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 What sort of work was that then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 
That - it was just the same work, he was a baker, journeyman baker - in Stornaway. And the - of course, once the - men was called up to the war, to the first world war and - money started - flowing in from the Government,
 things had changed. I quite believe that had my father had a little more patience - he would have done quite well.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Did he try to start a bakery of his own?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Well he had a bakery of his own there. Yes. Yes, but - of course in those days you see p
eople didn't have the money, and - they could do their own food mostly, their own produce, and - the mills of course, in every village there was a mill where they made meal out of their barley seed, and - of course they - the - they had boats, they had lo
ts of boats then for fishing, so that - they really - didn't require loaves in those days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Did your own family grow any of the food for yourselves?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Well we did, we had a croft of our own. And - of course we were different because my father was ba
king, we were different as far as - where the spread was concerned. But - of course my father didn't have time to - to attend mills in those days and there was quite near us there was a kiln, that's where they - they hardened - the seed, prior going to th
e mill with it. And - it used to be great fun to watch the old men - spending - spending days some - nights with a great big fire in the kiln, finding whether the seed was hardened before going to the mill with it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 This is a kiln for the barley?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 
For the barley seed, yes. Yes, and of course we used to get lots of fish then. I suppose people say that that's why - people in Lewis have - that they were pretty somewhat - well, brainy, because of the amount of fish, I wonder if there's anything in that
.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Could you tell me some typical days meals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 
Well we used to have porridge and milk in the morning. And then we had - we came home from school, we were able to come home from school for our lunch. Then usually we had - potatoes and fish sometimes
 or potatoes and - meat and - soup. And then we had tea, just similar to what it is today.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 How often would you have meat, just on Sundays or most days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Well I suppose we - we had meat always on Sundays. And during the week, it depended of cours
e we had - there were no fridges in the district then, it depended on when my father went to Stornaway.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 He would buy meat in Stornaway?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 He would buy meat in Stornaway, yes, he used to go there of course to get his own flour. And - and there was 
- he - he - he used to have a person helping him who would go to Stornaway, perhaps once a week, and he would go - himself another time. Well we usually brought meat - of course it was cheap in those days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Did you keep hens?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Yes, we had hens and
 we had a cow and hens, yes. But we didn't have - of course you see, most - people in those days, they had their own meat, but my father didn't have sheep because he had no time for looking after them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Who looked after the animals then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Well - w
e did ourselves, my mother, the - the cow - the animal was - the cow was - tethered in the croft. And then of course we used to go out - to the pastures, there was - the - the common grazing of the village, the cows of the village went down there and we u
sed to go with our own. Sometimes -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 The summer shielings you mean?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 No, not the shielings, that's different.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 You went down in the township?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Yes, the - you see, all the townships, they have their own grazing, common grazing, and - the ch
ildren very often had to go with the cows and herd them, especially during holiday time, and at the weekends we didn't like it very much. We had to do it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Did you grow your own barley then or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Well we had a little, yes, we had a little barley.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Did your father do that himself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Well, he got somebody else to do it for him, yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Did you grow vegetables?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Potatoes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Any others?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 But - but - just the potatoes and corn for the cow. Yes, cabbage, and turnips.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Did your mother make jam?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 I don't think so, I don't remember. Don't think so.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 What about wines and beer?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Well we didn't, but - it was quite a common thing in the village in those days, the old men - they were very very - adept at drink. Th
ey had ale. They made their own ale with barley. And it was - I remember drinking it. They used to - have a - a pebble - which they heated in the fire, and put it into it. It seemed to improve the taste of it. Oh I remember it quite well, yes. We didn't m
ake it, my father didn't make it at all, but I know - neighbours did. And - it was really a very good drink in the summertime. I remember when visitors came - came in the summertime, it was a great treat - for them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 You mean if visitors came to your own house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 
They went to the houses where they had - the ale, they always had a drink of ale for the visitors in those days. Yes, they used to - I think they used - yeast. And - the barley. I don't remember - I don't know how it was done but the - old m
en were very very good at it. Not every - not every man, but - quite a number of men in our village, quite a number were known for - for their skill - in - in - make - brewing this ale. Tea of course was quite common too in those days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Any tinned}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12143753\charrsid11559355  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 foods?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Not corned beef?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Did you have rabbit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Well there were plenty of rabbits, yes, yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 They shot seabirds, would your family have eaten the birds at all?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 No. No. Not in - that part. It's down Ness direction, used to go to one of the islands to - for the Solent geese.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Did your mother make medicines?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 
No, but - there was a minister, a reli - a minister of religion who retired to our village, and he was really very very skilful. And he used to t
reat all the people who were ill in those days. He was real - he really should have been a doctor. He - he was really wonderful. And - he was sent for - whenever there was illness - in - any of the houses, and - he always procured medicines for them, I do
n
't know whether he made it himself or - he had a stock anyway of medicines. Of course there was a doctor - in the parish, and he used to come to the school occasionally, I remember - when the - babies, the young children, were vaccinated, it was a great d
ay, the mothers used to come with the children to school and we used to - we - of course we got out, we were - looked forward to these days because it meant - freedom from lessons for a time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Could you tell me something about the housework at that time, would your mother do it all herself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Oh yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 She had nobody in to help?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 How many were there in the family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Just - there was three of us. Yes. Two boys and myself.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 So you would have to help her quite a lot?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Oh yes, I did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 What sort of jobs did she expect you to do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 
Oh well - I wasn't - asked to do very much to begin with but - I used to - well there was one thing that we had to do and that was - the water. We had to take the water in and that entai
led distances in summertime, because the wells round about - unless there was a fountain, the other wells, they dried up. But there was a well about - it'd be a mile - well - not quite a mile. Half a mile from us. And I can assure that our arms ached, and
 especially with us because my father required so much water - for his work.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Would the boys help too?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Yes, the boys, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Did the boys help in the house at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Not very much. No. Of course we were young when we left - Shawbost, my - younger brother was only seven years - when we left.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Were you expected to look after them a bit then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 
Yes, oh yes. And we used to help my father, it was a great - event for us to be allowed to turn - he had a machine for - the - dough for biscui
ts, we had to put it through the roller, and - we used - there was another family beside us, three boys, and they helped too, so - we used - away - as a reward we got - we got a piece of the dough what was left over and he - he - he cut it with three fing
ers and made a pleat of it. And he put - sugar on top and - some grease I suppose and then sugar and - oh it was a great treat for us in those days. We were very easily pleased then. We had to make our own - amusements and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 What sort of games would you play then as a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 
Well - just the games, skipping and - and - rounders, rounders were - it was a great - a favourite game. And - of course hide and seek and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Did you collect anything as a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Well we used to collect shells, and we used to make picture frames in school with them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 You didn't keep any pets?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 No. Well we had a - we had cats of course, and they were pets. But we didn't have a dog, seeing my father wasn't a shepherd.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 There weren't any entertainments, there obviously wasn't a cinema.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Oh no, not
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Were there any concerts?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Yes, there - there were concerts held then. I remember being taken to one by my father as a very - young girl.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Was that in the village?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 In the village, yes, yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Were you ever taken to Stornaway then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Yes. Yes. On market day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 That was a big treat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 That was a great treat in those days, yes. It was just like - going to Paris I think today.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Would your father take you there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Yes, my fat
her took me. In the summertime - it was customary for - the - it was cart and horse in those days, and for the Shawbost merchants cart and the bakers cart to go into town in the summertime to go at night - and see come back the following day, so that was 
t
he first time - that ever I went the first time I went to Stornaway. And - I remember it rained. Of course - that was a well known a well known fact that on market day, the first Tuesday of July, it was always wet. It was a great day really. It - it was s
omething you know that sticks in your memory all your life.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 What would be the other big days of the year as a child, was Christmas or was it really more Hogmonay?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Hogmonay of course, yes. Yes, Christmas of course we - we - well - with us - my fat
her used to - bring toys from Stornaway and - we'd put ours - we'd hang our stockings up, always, that was a great event in - in the morning, getting up early in the morning to see what Santa Claus had brought us and I remember how disappointed I felt whe
n I found it was no such person.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 And Hallowe'en?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 
Yes, we used to have that - well - yes, we used - we used to have Hallowe'en, oh yes, it's a great night, Hallowe'en night in the country then. Boys used to go into the - vegetable gardens and stea
l the - the turnips and - they used to have great fun throwing - and they would go to some house where they didn't have any vegetables and throw them in.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Would they put a candle in the turnip?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Oh they - not - no, not with us no. Not then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Was Easter important?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 No. No, there was nothing - at Easter, but - when was \{BLANK\}Yes. That's the old New Year isn't it. A great event.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 What was that then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Well - it was the boys of the village and - it was something like what they do - f
or - Hallowe'en. They - used to go round - the houses - and - the leaders, he had a - a skin, he carried a skin, a sheepskin. And - they had a rhyme. Of course in Gaelic. And - the housewife of course - gave them whatever she could give them, and they use
d to have a party afterwards. Something like Hallowe'en.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 You wouldn't take any notice of bank holidays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 No. No. Because we were - we didn't know anything about banks in those days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Would you go away for family holidays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 No. Well - oh the shieling in the summertime, yes, everybody in the - in the village went to the shieling. Yes. It's a great - time.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Can you tell me what it was like up on the shieling then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Oh it was - lovely. Did you see any of the - ruins of shielings? They
 - they weren't really - the old - the oldest - type was a beehive. But - that wasn't the kind of shielings that we had. They were just built - they were made of stone. And - a turf on the top. And - inside there were recesses, where they kept the basins 
o
f milk, because the - you see, they were so far out they didn't go home every day and they had to keep the milk and - take the cream off and collect the cream for taking home to be made into butter. It was really - it was a very free and - and ease - easy
 life, and it was lovely. I think the summers then were much better than the summers now today.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Did you gather in the evening?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Well it was - there was hardly any evening because - as you can see, there was hardly any night. They used to stay out 
for about six weeks.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Did you used to listen to the story telling up there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Well that would be in the wintertime, in the villages, oh yes, in villages that was done in the wintertime.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Did you participate in that as a child though?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Yes.
 Yes. Yes, I re - I remember how frightened I used to be listening to ghost stories, I wouldn't go home alone again. And that seemed to cling to me for a long time after I'd grown up too.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Would you go out with your parents, or just as children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 
Well we - we - we went with our own ages. Yes. There was, beside us there was a shoemakers house, and the daughter there was - about my own age, and of course I used to go there and she used to come to our house. But very often in their house were people 
coming with shoes, be quite a number of people in, my father used to go there too. And of course - they talked about all sorts of things. It was like a - a Parliament in our - on a small scale, discussing - the events of the - of the - of the day, of the 
w
orld or what had happened to themselves and - I suppose the - somebody would be reading - getting a paper and they would have heard the news and they were discussing all that and of course ghost stories - came into it as well. And we children of course li
stened with - our hair sticking on end.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Did they ever happen in your own house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Pardon?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Did they have this sort of occasion in your own house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Well sometimes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 But not so often?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 But not so often. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Did you in fact take a newspaper at that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 
I can't - I can't remember that we did. There was no - there wasn't - a - it was usually the schoolmaster or the minister. And the merchants who got a paper in those days. I don't remem - I do remember - not - in my -
 during my early days but I do remember the Peoples Journal coming. The Star of Robbie Burns, I remember that. That was a - a serial story. And - yes - yes, I remember that all right, we had - we did have it, but I - I can't remember off hand - there wasn
't a daily paper. That would be a weekly paper.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 There were quite a few books in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Oh yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Would your parents read aloud? To you as children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 No, not - well, my parents really hadn't the time, because my father - worked ve
ry hard, and my mother sometimes helped him. But I know that my father took great pains with me, and he had very little patience with me. A - arithmetic especially, I remember pounds shillings and pence.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 He tried to teach you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 He tried, yes, he
 was helping me with my - sums, I think I must have been - rather difficult - to begin with but I - I don't remember after, but he was very good with figures.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 And they took an interest in your schoolwork?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Oh they did, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Did they mind who you played with as a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 No. Oh no. Because we're all very friendly. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 What did they say if you happened to get dirty while you were out playing, would they be angry?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Oh no. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 She didn't mind at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 No, she wouldn't mind. It was taken for granted. The girls weren't as bad about that as boys.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Your father was very busy so did that mean he didn't ever help at all inside the house? Cooking, cleaning, that sort of work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Well - an uncle of mine used to help him. Bu
t he had his own family and - he would be with him for a time during the day, but then he had other commitments himself so that - it wasn't easy for him to - spend all the time, my father had to do and my mother helped with the cleaning of the - of the ba
ke}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12143753\charrsid11559355 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 house and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 In the home would your father actually help your mother with any of the housework?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Well - yes, to a certain extent, a little, not very much.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 What sort of things would he be prepared to do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Well he wouldn't do any cooking anyway, and I don't think he would do any cleaning.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Would he do the fires?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Oh yes, he would help, oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Would he help look after you children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Oh yes, when my mother went out. Yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 What about putting you to bed, would he ever do that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 
Well I don't remember. My memory doesn't go back as far as that. Oh he would, I quite believe he would do that, yes. I think most men would do that in those days you see, if they had to do it. But usually - it was the housewife who saw
 to all these things. The men of course - were always outside or - working.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Who would help if she was ill?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Well - we had - friends beside us, my - there was an aunt beside us. Yes. Yes. And then my father's people, they would help us if there wa
s - but we were very fortunate, we - I don't remember ever my mother being ill.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Were you expected to go to bed at a fixed time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Oh yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 What sort of time would that be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Oh then about ten o'clock anyway, yes. We were never out lat
er than that. Unless there was a - unless we happened to be - there used to be weddings of course, great weddings in those days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Could you tell me about a village wedding at that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Well it was quite a - a very jolly affair. They used to prep
are for days before hand, and they prepared all the food - themselves. Of course in the bride's house with as much help as they could get. They used to - have - chicken and - things to kill - one of their sheep or course or two, I don't know how many, and
 
- there used to be - great - a great number of people, of guests at the wedding. And - they had - then - everything - when everything was prepared - the - night before, the - tables were set. And - then the following day, the day of the - the marriage - e
v
erything was ready of course. And then the - proceeded to church. And they went in a - in procession wise. Every young man had a - lady. And - they all - perhaps in some cases they had to walk distances. The members that her way watch - used to watch the 
b
ride and see how she was dressed, and she used to have a - a bonnet affair on then. You - some of the Easter bonnets you see sometimes advertised in a paper, and - full of ribbons, coloured ribbons and - in those days it was a cape she wore. And - and the
n when - after the - ceremony they marched back to the home, where the feasting began. And then - then there was a barn, ready - made ready before hand for the dancing, and it used to go - perhaps sometimes for days.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Would everybody in the village go usually?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 
Yes, all the young, oh yes, and in the villages round about. It depended on the number of relations that they had of the - bride and groom had. It was a great affair, yes, but it meant a lot of hard work. Preparation of it. You don't have an
ything like that now. They all go to - the town now to get married.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Would people at that time call in, just drop in, or did they have to be invited?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Oh they dropped in, there was no such thing as invitations in those days. The people of the vill
age knew each other. We all knew - our neighbours and - the village people, we - we knew them all. And there was - friendly people. And was - they used to do a lot of the gathering in the houses in those days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Did your mother make or mend the family's clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 She made them. For the - for the - for - for me and for my brothers. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 That wasn't typical was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Well - well they had - yes it was, yes. Well - I was rather fortunate because my mother was really a natural dressmaker. Yes. Y
es she was. But - of course they knitted a great deal too. But - they made their own clothes in those days, they had to.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 There was a lot of spinning and so on wasn't there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 She wouldn't do the spinning?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 My mother? I remember my m
other making a tweed once. Yes. But - when they - they used to spin, they did a lot of that in the villages then. They - they used to make - tweeds, and sell them to - to augment the -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 The second of the side of the interview was not recorded due to a 
technical accident, I'm therefore noting some facts which she told me. Firstly, both her father and her mother came from Shawbost. Her mother had no work before or after she was married. Her father went into Stornaway in order to be trained as a baker, jo
u
rneyman baker, and started work there, then later returned to Shawbost. The house that they lived in at Shawbost had three rooms, that's a kitchen and two bedrooms. The washing was done at home, in the winter it was done in the house in a tub on the fire,
 
and in the summer the women would go down to the side of the loch and make fires, and the children would help and play around while the families were doing their washing. There was no regular washday, it depend on the weather. Arrangements for bathing wer
e
 similar. The family ate their in the kitchen and her mother cooked on an open fire. Birthdays in her childhood were recognized by some sort of very small presents but there were no parties for children. Her parents didn't play games with her. She would b
e
 sometimes taken out visiting friends and relations. Her parents thought it not wrong to either work or play on Sunday and she did wear special Sunday clothes. The whole family attended the Free Kirk. Mother, father and children, every week. They also sai
d
 grace before and after meals, and family prayers in the morning and evening. There were weekly prayer meetings. No other social activities organised by the church. She didn't belong to the choir. She did go to the Sunday school, so that she went three ti
m
es, twice to church and once to Sunday school on Sunday. Her father did take an interest in politics, he was a Liberal like the other people in the village and she does remember him voting for the Liberal party at a general election. She doesn't think tha
t
 he was a member of a political party. Her father worked long hours, so much so that her mother was in fact much more of an influence on her as a child. So that she didn't see much of him in the evenings. There were no clubs or pubs for him to attend, no 
s
ports. She knows of no savings clubs, or boot club or sick club. Similarly there were no youth organizations or sports for children. She didn't have a bicycle, even when she moved to Stornaway water. She didn't go fishing, that was something for boys. The
r
e was a policeman in the district, but they saw very little of him, unless there was some trouble when they did see him they felt rather frightened as children. At the Shawbost school the teachers would emphasise manners and tidiness. They didn't single o
u
t some children for different treatment from the others. They would use the belt for disobedience. She went on to another school afterwards, the Nicholson Institute in Stornaway which was also a mixed school and she went from there on to a college, traini
n
g college for teachers on the mainland. The move to Stornaway brought a strikingly new environment to her and she didn't in fact find that there was so very much more for a teenage girl to do than in the village, there was no theatre in Stornaway, no cine
ma, and there wasn't any kind of teenage parade as in English towns on Sunday.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Would you like to say your name?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Well my name is Kathleen Finlayson.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Did you start school at six?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Five. Started at five. Yes, it's always five in this - in - in the island here Yes. All children begin at five.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 That's a full day at five?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 
Yes, well - yes, but - with the infants they're supposed to - be finished about - three o'clock. But of course with - where they're dependent on conveyances now it
 - most of them are, especially here - they can't get home then and they have to - they're just keep in 'til the other children go at four o'clock.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 You walked to school didn't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Yes, as children - oh yes, we walked to school, yes. There was no conveyance in those days. We weren't very far from the school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Did you like the school or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Yes, I liked school very much, yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 I think that you said that in the school the boys did form sort of groups and have fights among themselves and so on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 
Oh - well yes, now - well not so much a - against - among themselves as - with - from a different part of the village, but there wasn't really anything like what we have today, they were quite friendly. They had their - quarrels like 
- like all children, but it was quite a - they were soon friends again.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 It was sort of fooling around?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 
Yes, exactly, yes. And they were very - another thing - at that time of course they were all very big boys. They were just men, they seemed to
 be much bigger than the children of that age today. Of course they stayed longer in school, in a primary school there were there until fourteen. And that would make a difference because there weren't - there weren't - there were - of course there was tha
t
 - that pass that got - the qualifying exam - passed the qualifying examination got - were sent to the - Nicholson Institute - in my day. But - majority of them of course - and in those days there wasn't really much help for them. Especially, they had a b
u
rsary but it was a very meagre amount, and - the parents found it difficult - difficult to keep them, because they were away from home all the time and there was no provision at least - apart from the bursary made for them, they had to - provide them with
 clothes and - so if the parents that - but certainly if there was a very bright boy the parents did everything they could for him. Even sold their - their stock in order to provide him, and especially when they went to uni - college or university.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 So in your time you felt the parents were really quite enthusiastic?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 
Oh they were, for their child that was - that had it in him. Oh yes, and - it's amazing - well - there were many others that could have done very well who didn't get the opportunity, 
through financial - difficulties of course. Lack of finances I should say you know. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Did you feel that at the school there were any children who were left out of things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 No, no there weren't, no. Everyone was given a chance. And we had very 
good teachers. Yes. I can't say - anything else about them, the same in the Nicholson too.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Before you went to school did your parents try to teach you anything like the alphabet or counting or something?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Well my father did - my father - taught m
e the letter - well - tried to teach - in those days of course it was quite common to do that. Yes. But - well it wasn't common, I shouldn't say that, but some parents did. That - it was a great help in those days, and especially - words, English words, t
he English equivalent of words, that - nowadays of course they can't do that. Children are taught so differently.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 There's a custom in England called rough music, when there's somebody who's disapproved of in a village people go and bang pots and things
 outside the house and sort of try and get them to go off, was there anything of that kind?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 No, there wasn't, no, no, never came across anything like that, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 It doesn't seem to have been used here.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 No.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Then the social structure of the village, there was the Proprietor?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Yes. An absent.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 He was an absent?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 So he played no part?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 No. Not in - no, he didn't. In our part we - it was different, we'd different areas, the Lodge people here they had - those - ca
ttle people who had the lease of the Lodge there, they used to give children, you know, parties at Christmas especially but we had no - no such thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 So that you never really saw the Proprietor at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 No, I don't ever remember seeing him.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 I think you said that therefore the most important people would be the ministers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 
Yes, the minister and the Elders and - doctor of course and teacher, and the head teacher, and the teachers too, they were respected and looked up to in those days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 And the merchants I think you mentioned?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 
Well - yes, and those who got on and had - well - it depended on their - their own - on their character, because we knew from our parents people that we had to - show respect to. And then of course all chur
ch members of the church. Especially the Elders and they saw to it that the young people behaved as well, and especially on Sunday, because it was an unknown thing for - to see anyone - outside except going to church. In the village.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 You mean that they would visit a family if they saw a child outside?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 
Well I don't know if they would then, not that day but - well - it wouldn't matter about a child being outside as long as the child was behaving but there was nothing done outside on Sunday at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 You mentioned that the poorest people usually were the older people who had no pension?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 
Well - I mentioned not only old people, no, but - well it was usually who had no one to - no one to look after - especially - ladies - women that weren't marr - that hadn't got married and you were - in straitened circumstances.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 I think that you said that you were brought up to believe that one should give to people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Yes, oh yes, we - did help, of course I know that - my own father, he was very kin
d hearted and - anybody that was in distress - he would help.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Were there any squatters or cotters in your village?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 No, apart from these people who - I told you that - their friends built a small house, small cottage for them. No, I - I don't kno
w of any squatters in the - in - in the village in which I was brought up myself in those days because everybody - had a croft. And of course they had - animals, cows and sheep. And they had their own - meat. And - they cured it and had it during the wint
e
r. Because in those days you didn't get fresh meat because there were no butchers in the country parts. Today of course everybody - gets - gets the butchers go round but - in those days there was no such thing, but everybody had their own. And it was quit
e a - a common thing for them to - sometimes they would buy a cow between a number of them. And - get it slaughtered and - salt the beef of it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 They would divide it up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Yes, well perhaps four people share, quarter each. That was quite a common th
ing. Especially those that were able to do it, but most people had their own sheep. And - had their own meat, they used to have barrels of meat in the wintertime.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Would you feel that there was any important difference between the people who went to th
e St Cedars and the people who went to the free Kirk, or were they very much the same?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 
Well - there were no Suceeders in my day - at this - not in our - the village I came from was - not divided - religiously. It was just one church, the Free Church,
 but - there were a few families, especially - the teach - the head teacher and - these people who were more or less superiors in the village, they usually belonged to the United Free Church, and that as it became afterwards the Church of Scotland. But - 
as far as I know - of course the - the Free Church and the Suceeders have some what - supposed to be - somewhat narrow minded, but more so the - Free Presbyterians. But we had no connection with them at all in my young days. In my young days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 So it was unusual in being a united village in that way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 
Yes, well - but - there's really no difference between the people in their social life, none whatsoever, I suppose - the only - difference between them were - was when they came to discuss the - the pri
nciples of their own different churches, but as children we knew nothing about that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Could you tell me about the preparations you would make on Saturdays for Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Well - we had to - the house was cleaned, we had - scrubbing to do, would do -
 usually was a bench on which we - people sat, in the kitchen. And - the table from which the food was taken, it was scrubbed white every Saturday. Chairs and stones and - the kitchen tidied, and the water taken in, we had to fill vats of water, and pails
 
and these were of course stored - inside in the little hall inside, well the little - recess, and there was - covered and we had to take in the peats and stack them up at the door. For all that would do Sunday for us. All that was done. And then you - and
 then of course it was the night on which we all would - got bathed and - changed our - underclothing, the whole family.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 So really it was almost the hardest working day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Yes, yes, in that respect, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Was there any way as a child that you could earn some pocket money, I think you said about running errands?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Yes, running errands, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 That was really the only way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Yes, that was the only way, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 So you wouldn't have regular pocket money, you didn't have a penny a week or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 No, we didn't have anything - regularly like that but we - always managed to have sweets and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Where would you buy sweets?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Oh well there was a shop in the village, yes. There were several shops in the village in my yo
ung days. Yes. Yes, there were - three at any rate, or four. Be - there were four shops - in the village.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Were these run by crafting families?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Yes. Yes. Well there was one, he was the Postmaster and the - merchant, he had a shop as well. And inc
identally his son carries it on to this day. And - just the crofters, yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Did your mother have any interests outside the home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 I can't say that she had except just the church itself. Now, there was nothing like that, there was no social - well
 - there was very little social life mostly, there was nothing done in the village. They were fully - the women were fully occupied. You must remember that they had to do everything. They had to be - well, my mother of course didn't but - the women - they
 
had to do their own baking and - well - very often there was a big family, and in the - summertime, they - of course the women did their own good share of the work outside as well as the work - of the house. Now the men usually - the crofters, usually - w
ent to the east coast fis}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1643878\charrsid11559355 h}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 
ing, in the summertime. Now the women and the children carried on. Now, their crofts were very very extensive then, barley and oats and potatoes, and the peats as well. And the cows to look after, perhaps to go to the shieling with
 them. And the work of the house. Now, the women were very occupied, they were knitting always and sewing, baking, and washing and - we often wonder how - today we wonder how they really did it. When - when - you think of what a housewife - well, all the 
gadgets we have today to help us with the - with the housework.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Would you feel then that the men had more time to spare for caeligs and so on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Well the - the men had certainly because the man, when his work - he certainly worked hard during the d
ay, but when he did come in - and his - tea or his supper when he could just sit down and enjoy his pipe and - and go caelig whereas the woman couldn't. And I'm afraid too there was a - too much of that. I think there was - the men were more or less encou
r
aged - the women - had to attend upon them - more, in this island especially. I think it was - all over, because the men - were attended upon hand and foot, of course the idea was that the men worked hard. Women perhaps the work that they did wasn't - it 
w
asn't - didn't entail so much strength as - the fishing out in the boats and going out to mid ocean and - then all the other work they had to do, turning the ground and - but there were all - commonly - there - there was such big families then. A small fa
mily would be about four or so. Usually eight and ten. And you wonder today how they were fed, when you think of it. And they were all -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 You never felt your parents had a struggle though to make ends meet as far as food went?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 No. Well - no. But - my father wasn't really prosperous, I told you that because of the circumstances.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 But you didn't feel that as a child?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 No. Oh no, we didn't, we had - food. And clothes and - we were - we weren't well off, what you would call - comparing it wit
h today. We certainly weren't but we were quite comfortable.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 You were allowed to talk during meals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 
Oh yes, yes. We was allowed to talk - we talked of things - of - whatever had - the days doings or school or - yes, but we weren't encouraged to 
- to report anything, I mean, tell tales or even to tell that we had been misbehaving in school and had got the strap or - if the boys did that you see they would get no sympathy. And that was quite common all over I think. Not only in Lewis but everywher
e. Because your parents would say, well you - if you got the strap you deserved it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 You were expected to eat the food that you were given, you couldn't sort of choose a bit here and choose a bit there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Oh well - if there was anything that we liked we could. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 What did your mother say when you didn't eat all the food that was given to you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 
Well - I suppose in those days we did - because we didn't have a variety then, as we have today. And - certainly if there was a member of the famil
y that - couldn't take it, there was something else. I had a brother who wouldn't take what we all took. And my mother saw to it that - he had - he had - something that he liked. Because she knew that it was - his stomach did not - his - his - his stomach
 
would be upset. Especially, there was one thing that - I always remember soup - vegetables. He didn't like them at all. So - there was something else. At least the stew - the soup would be strained for him so that he wouldn't get vegetables in it. Well an
y
thing like that - I mean - I suppose if we didn't take our food she knew there was something very far wrong with us. She'd be quite concerned about that because we were healthy, and - we - we had good appetites. I mean we were always out. We were - health
y, and the food we had was wholesome and we didn't know - of course - we may have been better off because we had - loaves and biscuits and - things that my father made. Whereas other children didn't.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 You were able to ask for a second helping it you wanted it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Oh yes, if you wanted more, yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 I think you said that your mother did teach you to you're your knife and fork and sit in a certain way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Yes, oh yes, yes. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 You were expected to wait until the end of a meal before leaving the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Oh yes, yes. Yes, we weren't allowed to - rise from the table until the grace was said. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Did you have the same places at table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Oh yes. Yes, we always sat in the same place. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 And your mother would serve the food?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 I think you said that your mother was really more influential than your father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 
Well we were more with my mother, yes, my father would be - we were oftener with our mother I think. But my father - I don't know really becau
se - we were more afraid of our father than we were of our mother, because a cough even sometimes from our father was enough to make - sit up and take notice you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 If you had done something naughty how would your mother punish you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Well - we would get punished with - we'd - we'd get caught with a punishment then. Yes. If we deserved it. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Would that be not very often?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Oh no. No. I don't remember much about that. No, I don't.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 You do remember it having happened sometimes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Yes, yes, I have a - faint recollection of it. But - I was - reprimanded on many occasions.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Her usual way was to reprimand you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Yes, that was - yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 And similarly with your father would that be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 You did find it quite easy to talk to your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Oh yes. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 And bring worries to her?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 
Yes. Well - my mother was a bit reserved certainly, and - we did - well - I suppose if a young person you - you don't talk to much to your mother until afterwards, my mother 
and I were left together you see. And - we were more like two sisters. She knew all my problems and my - worries. But in my young days I - they was - they were carefree days and - I don't - remember really very much about - I suppose if I was - if I had a
ny worries I would - ex - tell her and - expect to be - helped by her.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 But it was her rather than your father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Oh yes, it was my mother, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 You told me what they emphasised as important in life, I think truthfulness you mentioned?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Ye
s, honesty, my father was - very much - emphasised - honesty, he was very very honest himself, and - we were taught that, we were - advised, given very good sound advice. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 And no swearing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Oh swearing wasn't allowed at all. No. I must - can'
t say that we were - well perhaps the boys were, I mean, they would be hearing it outside but - I - I haven't heard - I can't say that I heard - swearing - given vent to in our own house at any time. I know it wouldn't be tolerated.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Were you allowed to talk when grown ups were talking?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 
Well - no, we weren't, we were - kept in the background. We had to. We - we were - we were to listen but - or usually if they - of course if they wanted to discuss anything - important we weren't allowed to stay in the room.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 You used this form to .....?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 
To older people. Yes. And children - the children were - from their childhood were taught that. Yes. Because it was considered even to hear that - a person - using the familiar form to their parents, it was considered - not right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 
But there weren't any special forms of respect that you would show to the minister for instance, this is the main thing, you talked familiarly to people of your own age and respectfully to your elders?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Well I don't thi
nk in those days that we did really do very much speaking, we were too shy - to speak, I mean, except and - just to answer the questions we were asked in a respectful way. We were taught to just to - answer questions. Politely. Of course we - we would nev
e
r think of - addressing the minister. Oh no we couldn't. No, we certainly wouldn't. Never dream of doing that. As children. Oh no we wouldn't. We'd just answer their questions, they would meet - he would meet us, I remember very well the gentleman who was
 
there at that time. And - he would always - speak to us and we - answered him politely. Now this other - minister who was our - who should have been a doctor, well - I - I've a - a very vivid memory of him. He was our - very nice looking old man with a be
a
utiful white beard, and white hair. And in those days - we thought he was just like God - a picture of God. And he was so nice to us - always, and - he had a wonderful garden, and we used to stand there on our way to school admiring - plants he had. And h
e always came out and spoke nicely to us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Was there anyone that you were brought up to feel was sort of a real gentleman, I'm not sure if there is a phrase in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1643878\charrsid11559355 G}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 aelic like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Oh yes, yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Who would that be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Oh well, there were c
ertain people in the village who were - outstanding. Yes, oh church Elders of course they were. We - they - yes, yes, and - no, yes, and local village people too. They were outstanding.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 It was more a question of character than occupations for example?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 
Yes, well - we knew from our parents - because we used to hear them talking about them. And - they themselves showed them respect so we knew that they were outstanding.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Did you make this division which is usual in an English village between the rough and the respectable?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 
Oh yes. Yes, certainly, yes. And - it was very noticeable, at - weddings especially, you know, that - if there was a dance - the - the - the behaviour - the behaviour of the young people then. Well if there - there were - 
perhaps in a village some that were - out - rowdy and they were not liked at all. But there was - a few. That - very often at any affair of that kind they seemed to - cause trouble. Now they were the same people, and - the rest of the village looked down 
upon them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Would those also be people who quite often there was some drunkenness in the family or something like that?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Oh yes. Yes, there would be but - yes, well there was that of course that used that, weren't liked. Used - that used it - but 
- in - in the village I was brought up in - I know that - they were marked more or less those that caused trouble, and - they weren't liked at all. But - I must say in that village that the people - at all these affairs, they behaved very well. And - enjo
yed themselves and the - the weddings especially - were most enjoyable. And they were very very hospitable too - to strangers who came - guests who came from other parts.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 What about funerals at that time, or don't you remember one?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Oh yes, yes, I remember funerals.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Would the whole village go to a funeral?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 
Oh yes, yes, even to this day they do that. I was at a funeral - a week ago, a week last Friday, and - I don't think I ever saw more people at a funeral. Than I did that day. Very symp
athetic towards people that are bereaved, especially if - if it's a sudden - death where - well a young person especially.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Did they have the two days after the death before the funeral when people could visit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Yes. Yes. Well this person, he died
 on the - Wednesday I think, Wednesday morning, and he - when he died in Stornaway, it was a very sudden death, and a very pathetic - sad - death it was, and he was buried on Friday morning - well, in the forenoon, twelve.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 It would still be considered indecent to bury somebody they day they died.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Oh they don't do that on the island at all, they don't do that. And the people there they're - really very sympathetic and - they -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 And they would have stayed up at night.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Yes, they used to st
ay up at night, yes. But they don't do that so much now, of course the houses are different. I don't know what the reason for it was, but I think - some people said - I heard that - in the very olden days - I suppose - in the dark - black houses - that - 
that might be vermin. And that that was why the - the - corp}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1643878\charrsid11559355 s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 
e was watched but - of course that must have been long long long ago, because - and then somebody else said but that couldn't have been in Lewis. They used to - steal bodies. That may have been, t
hat - of course I don't know. But - it was quite a common thing, to stay up for - pay - the people of the village came in, and stayed up all night. And the bereaved people - they were very much helped because - you know, they felt - somebody being in beca
use there's something very eerie about death.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 That's probably why they did it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Yes, quite likely it was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 So there'd be quite a few people in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Yes. Yes, there used to be, but nowadays with - the different houses, and the peop
le, there aren't so many people now. But I don't know whether they do it, I think they do it in some places yet.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Did the women come to the funeral?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Yes, well the relations, the - people who are related to the - to the - one who - to the - person
 who has died or to his - wife if he is married.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 The women didn't actually go to the cemetery?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 
No, no, the women just go in there, for the funeral, and - they usually - stay with the - bereaved people for a - while they have a cup of tea with them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Can you tell me about the communion services?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 
Oh yes. Well as a child it was - a very different - it was very different to what it is today. The communion - begin here on - Thursday. And there are two services every day, Thursday and Friday.
 On Saturday there's one service, well - but there's a - a - prayer meeting - in the evening. Then on the Sabbath - there's communion - in the morning, and then there's the - service in the evening. And then on Monday - the last service of the communion. 
N
ow in my day in my young days, my - the - Wednesday before communion - was our - just like Saturday - on an ordinary weekday. Because every preparation was made. And Thursday, it's known as fast day. I believe in the olden days - they fasted. And they did
 
not eat any food until they came ho - back from church, and in those days, the session was very very long. And especially in a district like this where the people had to walk miles. But I don't remember anything like that. There was no fast day - in my da
y
. In my - young days. Now I remember distinctly - and in those days, the house of course - was cleaned, and very often we papered it, and - everything was done, now - on the Wednesday - the Wednesday was a very busy day, because - the women - had to do al
l
 the starching then, because the men wore in those days stiff collars and cuffs, and I remember my mother doing that with a box iron. And - everything had to be taken in just like a Saturday - and then on - Thursday - there was nothing done at all, of cou
r
se the dinner was cooked. If my mother went to church - well in - when we were young - she would have prepared the dinner, and just would have to boil the potatoes after she came home. But - there was nothing done all week except just the nec - necess - w
h
at was necessary. And of course there were visitors you see, they came - they came from - the different parts of the island and stayed during the communion week. And - these people were with us - staying - very often staying - they stayed at night, and ha
d their meals. And that's done to this day.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 How many people would you have staying with you on an occasion like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Well, in some houses there'd be quite a number, it depended on the house you see. Where there - there were Elders, you see - th
ey used to have quite a number of people. We would have, I suppose - one or two staying with us. But in some of the other houses there'd be quite a number.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 How often were these?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Twice a year, every spring and every autumn.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Why was it that people came to stay?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 
Well you see, in those days you see, there - there was no con - con - there - there weren't conveyances, and then they wanted to stay and - listen to all the - to the ministers there. It was usually the - the - communicants who ca
me, those who were - of course others came as well. It depended of course if they were at home, but - the - those who were members of the church, they came, those that were able to come, now they had to walk miles and miles some of them. So that - it was 
easier for them to come - to - to arrive there on the Thursday morning, and stay until Monday afternoon.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 There are churches in each village, what I don't quite understand is why people had to come from other villages?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Well you see, their own - ho
w do you mean? The reason for it was you see - it wasn't the - they had different ministers, at every communion - the minister of the congregation invites other ministers. Now some ministers were more attractive than others you see. And people clocked to 
hear them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 So each village would have its communion service at a different time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 
Oh yes, yes. Oh yes, yes, you see they - the - the - they begin - with the Stornaway communion. Stornaway communion first, and - in the - in the spring time, its on 
the third Sunday of February. Now, the others come in - in - rotation after that, Shawbost and all the other - the - you never have two - well there are sometimes two communions, but they're in different parts of the island. There might be one at Ness and
 
one at Lochs. But that's only on - two or - two occasions I think. Because - then - that is from - from - the third - the last - the third - Sabbath of February, until the first of April. Now the last communion's on the first of April. The first Sunday of
 
April. Then in the autumn time again - this always coming in - is - the first - the last Sabbath of August - and - they're spread out again to the first Sabbath of November. So you got ever so many - there's Stornaway, Stawbost, Carlaway - Barvus, Ness, a
 number at Locks, Bark, Point, you see, all these coming in - they're - they're - crammed into that - period.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 You say that some of the adherents would come too?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Yes, some - oh yes. And - nowadays - you see, life has changed so much now - that yo
u see today people are working. And - only those that aren't working - of the members, can come to the nearest - communion, coming into the nearest place where the communion is held. But on Sunday - they come in great numbers - with their cars. They come 
during - at night too, during the week. Like, they're able to come after work. But in the olden days you see the lack of conveyances, they had no conveyance, many of them had to walk. Unless they got a ride in a cart.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 So it must have been a very import
ant occasion with so many people in the village. There wasn't anything else happened at that time except for the services?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Oh no, there wasn't.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 There would be no caeligs for instance at that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 No, no, the - people weren't - went to chu
rch separate. They would be gathering in a - in - some houses, you know, perhaps in an Elders house, one of the Elders, they'd be gathering there and having a meeting between themselves.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 A sort of prayer meeting?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Yes, oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 And maybe discussing the Bible?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Oh yes, and discussing perhaps what they - require, and then see on Friday it's question day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 What happens then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Well on Friday morning - the services begin at twelve, and - after the - the - there's singing first and the
n a prayer. And then - the minister who's officiating reads a chapter. And then - he asks one of the Elders of the - of the - church, of that church, to - give a portion of scripture for con - for the - questioning. Now he gives out one of the text - a te
x
t on the Bible, he chooses it himself, and this is for - talking on, and - the minister has a list of the names of the strangers who have come from other congregations and he calls upon them to give their - experience and to - talk on this question. And i
t's very interesting - to listen to them. They give their own experience.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Would this also be the time when the people make a profession of faith or is that at a different time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Well sometimes they do. But - oh no, you mean, by the questions?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 I meant during this communion?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 
Well - it very often happens that - during the - preaching - during the communion week that somebody has - a few could be arrested more or less. But I don't think any profession then, you see - it takes a time before they are - able to do that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 What happens then, are they visited by an Elder?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 
Well - to begin - to - to begin with I suppose it's a private matter - with a person. And then the first - sign is - when that person - attends - the prayer meeting dur
ing the week, there's a - there's a - in all the villages - the bigger villages of the island - there's a - usually Wednesday night, there's a prayer meeting in the church, and it's the members that go there. None of the adherents go. But if there's someb
o
dy who's serious minded - and who - is - arrested - that's the first sign, when he - he or she attend - attends the - prayer meeting. Now that goes on for a time. Until the person and of course the - the Elders - until he talks to the Elders - until he ta
l
ks to the Elders and so on, until such a time as he feels that he has - that he has been freed from his - well, from - from the life that he has been living that year - that he - he has - had liked on the matter. And then he goes before the Session if he 
w
ants to partake of the Lord's supper, and become a member of the church, he has to - now - the - he has to meet the - the Elders. Now the minister - proclaims that from the pulpit - on - the first day of the communion, that - the E1 - the Session is open 
f
or any person who feels - that they would like - to witness for the Lord - and the person, if he gets or she gets the strength to do that - they come before the Session. Session's made up of - the Elders of the church. And - he's questioned there. On Sund
ay again - he or she - sits at the Lord's table for the first time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 In your childhood would most of the heads of households have become members of the church?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Oh no. No, not most of them, no. No. But - in all these churches throughout the island 
it's amazing the number that are - if you happen to be - in church on the Sabbath of the communion - there - the - there are - the pews are marked you see, for those who are partaking. And you'd be amazed at the number of people. Of course, maybe stranger
s there as well.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Could you just say your name and then I'll play it back?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Yes. Yes. You want me to say my name is it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Could you tell me what year you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Yes. I was born in 1898. In - during Queen Victoria's reign. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Was that somewhere around here?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Yes. Right here.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 In this very house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 
Yes. Well - not exactly in this building but - in a house nearby there. And - I lived mostly all my life here. My - only schooling I got was in Crowbista - public school. A
nd - from there I was - I was brought up on a farm here. Estate working, and for - for - and far - farming. I was helping - I was helping my father. Then - this - farm here was broken into - small holdings after the first world war. For - to - to enable u
s
 to - to settle ex-servicemen on the land, so that - we - we - got the farmhouse, this very house where you're in just now, and thirty-two acres of land - attached to it. We call it up here crofts or small - smallholdings, there isn't much difference. And
 - things - things have changed very much since - since I remember it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Was your father a kind of farm manager?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Yes. Yes, he was - he was a farm manager.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 How many acres was that farm?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Oh - well over seven thousand acres. Yes, that - that included hill - hill pastures.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Was it a sheep farm?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 A - a sheep farm. Well - sheep - sheep and cattle. Yes. But - it was - mostly sheep. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 How many men were there working that farm?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 There - they use - they used to have - two or 
three men, steady hands as we used to say, we used to call them firm hands, and then - seasonal. There may be - three or four men - others engaged - now for - for heavy work like handling sheep, shearing - all that was - as it is yet - done by hand. Now t
h
at - that en - entailed a lot of work, then - the ingathering of crops. Oats and hay. And potatoes. I remember - what we called a creel, that weighed over a hundredweight. I remember - as we say here, lifting over two hundred creels in a season. That was 
q
uite a big - a big a - a big affair. And in winter - always the sheep had to be - looked after. But - it - it meant work out for - two or three men, because the - the cold was - so - it was - it was - sheep are so stupid. Well - I remember working for - f
irst of all it was - a Mrs Macleod who had this house. Then - she left in 1916, turned the place over to - Colonel Matheson of the Lewis. And then - the Department of Agriculture's took over.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 So the owner before the Department of Agriculture was who?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Colonel Matheson.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 That's the descendant of Sir James Matheson?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Did you see him at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Pardon? Well - at that time - of course - I remember seeing him. Because we - in my younger days he - he used to come periodically, 
in his, what we called coach and pair. They - they used to get - excited see - see - seeing this gentleman in kilts. Oh this was - this was - we - we - he - he was the superior of Proprietor, he had the whole of - he - he had the whole of Lewis. Well - th
en - that was before the famous Lord Leverhulme bought it. Yes. He - he - he appeared on the scene 1919. Yes, I remember him well. Yes. Yes, I was speaking to him, remember seeing him in - at Stornaway Castle. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Did your mother come from this part?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Yes. Yes. From Crowbista. Her - her maiden name was Macleod. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Did she do any paid work before she was married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 No, no, well - apart from - from dom - domestic work.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 She did do that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Yes, yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Did she go to the mainland then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 No, I don't so. I don't think so.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Then after she was married she just worked in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Yes. Well - well we had a - she had a large family. I was the youngest. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 How many brothers and sisters did you have then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 There was - there were five sons - sons. In the family, and two girls.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Did she have anyone to help her in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 No. No. Oh she - she managed herself. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Were you boys expected to help at all inside the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 No, no, not much.
 No. In - in those far off days - we had no laid on waters, we had to - to carry it from the well. Well that was the - after coming from school - good work for boys. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 What other kind of jobs did you have to do as a boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Well - not - really - really - taking in peats, that's - small jobs like that. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Would your father help inside the house as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 No, he did - he - he didn't have to. No. No, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 What about taking you boys out by yourselves or something like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Did 
- with my father? Of course we do that, yes, yes, yes, because - I happened to be the - the - the youngest - and I was always - helping him, he was - he was getting up in years while I was - while I was - quite a young - boy. I remember helping him with t
he plough. The old - swing plough with a pai}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1643878\charrsid11559355 r of horses. And - scything, ten}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 
ding hay with your hands now. There were no - there were no mechanical appliances then. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Can you tell me about the meals in the family, could you tell me a typical day's meals? What you would eat.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 
Yes. We used to - we - we used to have very wholesome fare. Yes, we had porridge and milk - and - those - of us who would - who would like - a good cup of tea after that. Yes, and then - usually for the dinners, good Scotch Br
oth. And - potatoes. And a big old - a - a jug of milk, fresh milk along with it. Those of us - of course it was left to - to - to our own individual - some of us wouldn't like milk after, but -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 How often would you have meat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Meat? Nearly - nearly every day of the week. Yes, we'd have plenty of that. Our own meat. Yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 And did you have fish?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Would they be fished here then, would they be caught here?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Yes. Yes, yes, in the - the nearest village, the - Crowbista
. I remember - three - three fishing boats fishing out - they - they used to fish for ling. And - cure it in the - they had a curing house in the village there. It used to be sent on to Glasgow at the end of the season. Now - the - the fishermen have plen
t
y of other - smaller fry - wasn't - that wouldn't be - saleable - it wouldn't be - I don't think - I don't think it - it will fetch that much on the - on the - market - in the - in Glasgow or whatever - or wherever it was sent to. With the result that - p
eople had plenty of fish, and then we - we used to fish ourselves with - with rods - on the - on the rocks here, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Were you allowed to get the fresh fish, the salmon?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Oh no. No, no, no. Oh - if - if we had attempted that we would - we would lose our hair. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 You had rabbits then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Yes, the - the - the - the fields were - just - crawling with them. Yes. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Geese you caught?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Oh yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Hens?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Oh wild geese?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Yes. But - we - we - we used 
to carry a shotgun - around with a couple of dogs. Then - there was - there - in - in winter there used to be a lot of - migrating birds, geese and - wild duck and of course - the stag was pro - protected. And there - and there again though. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Hares?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Did you shoot them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Yes, with a gun, yes, oh yes. Yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Did they keep pigs on the farm?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Yes. Just to - for their own use. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Most people around here don't seem to have done.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Just for the farm?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 
Yes, be - because - it was an expensive item, get - getting pigs - getting pigs here, they would have to come from Tingwell or Ness. So - even then - the pig was - out of the question. For - for - for - for most people.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Can you tell me about the 
way in which the meals were served, would you all sit at the table? You all sat together at the table and started with grace?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Did the other men working on the farm eat with you or did they eat separately?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 No, the - but when - the
y - there used to be two - two hand - two hands, what we called steady hands, and - two dom - domestics - two girls, yes. Well - in the farmhouse, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 They lived in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Oh yes. Yes. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 So the workers ate in the farmhouse, they had a separate - they cooked for themselves?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 They had - they had a - they had - what we called servants quarters. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 In your own family were you allowed to talk at meals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Of course, yes, yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 If you didn't like the food that you were given and didn't eat it, what did your mother say, did she mind?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 No, no, no. No. The food we always had was very - was so very wholesome and very well cooked. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Was she strict about the way that you sat at table? The way that you held your knife and fork?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 
We - well from - from early childhood - we were taught - how to behave. Yes. Yes. Not a - not a - not a spoon would be lifted until the grace was said, at the beginning and at the - at the end. Yes. So that - we - we were allo
wed to discuss the topics of the day or - anything like that. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Your mother baked her own bread?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Oh yes. Oh yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Did she make jam?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Rhubarb. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Did she make any wines or beer?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Oh no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 No beer made in the family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 No..
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Did she make medicines?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 
No, not - not my mother in particular. Although - I daresay - some mothers - I don't know if - if it was - really - the old ladies who - who used to - what we call those now mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 There were old ladies in the village who made medicines for other people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 There was no - no - there was nobody in the village - but ourselves.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Who were the old ladies then? From other villages?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Yes, Crowbista. My - my mother came from Crowbista, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Would these be midwives too perhaps?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 
Some of them would be. There was one - thing that they made when a person suffered from - a bad stomach. I think it was the Golden Saxiphrage. And - they boiled it. And bottled the juice of it, I don't know what
 they added to it, and it was supposed to be very good - for stomach trouble. Yes. Oh - I remember - seeing that - I remember a - an old gentleman here - getting that - it - it grew in - generally stagnant waters. Just - just a - a weed about that - yes. 
N
ow they - they used to - to put it in the - in the water and then - it was allowed to - to dry, in the house, for about a week. Then - it - it was - put in a pan, about - well I - I - to - to boil, I really don't know how many hours. Until all the - all t
he juice came out. Then - that was bottled. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 K2  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Mrs. F. That was something I forgot to tell you actually, we were very fond of dulce, shell }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid12386689\charrsid11559355 \endash }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355  sea}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12386689\charrsid11559355 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 
wood, a - a certain kind of seaweed, and - and - there was another time - when this was - it wasn't - it
 didn't grow very tall, it was brown. It was very very good. Dulce we called it - called it, I don't know if you know it. Well we - used to go right into the seashore and get some. We used to eat it. And there was another kind of - of - seaweed. It wasn't
 
really the tangle. We called it milka. It was - it was like black sugar in the centre, and there was a - you know the edges, the - like frills along the edge, perhaps you saw something like it. Now, I remember an incident a few years ago, a girl from Stor
n
away, and - in a certain village the postman had come - from one part of the village to the post office over the beach, he came out - across the beach, and he got some of this, and he had taken the frilled part away and he was - eating this part and he sh
owed it to her, and she asked what - what brand it was. She thought it was bought in a shop. But we were very fond of that.</subject2>
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 That was what you had instead of chewing gum and sweets.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Yes. We had -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 You used to shellfish a lot here.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Yes, and we did too. Yes, barnacles. And - whelks.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Mr. F. Now - now - now - be - before we leave the sea}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12386689\charrsid11559355 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 wood, what about carrick?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 K2  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Mrs F. Carrick, oh yes, oh yes, well we didn't know about carraking.</subject2>
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 What's that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Anot
her seaweed. You could get it in the shops as Irish malt. And - It's very rich in iodine, and it's also a remedy for indigestion. Yes. And you could make a - something like }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12386689\charrsid11559355 \endash }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355  corn}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12386689\charrsid11559355 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 flour, you can make a pudding of it.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Mr. F. A - very nice pudding. You put - oil in the middle.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 K2  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 
Mrs. F. And it's lovely. Oh yes, we sometimes have it. But - we didn't know about it in the part I came from, I never heard of it 'til I came here. But we had it every year. We have to - pick it, and then bleach it. And - u
ntil it's quite - crisp, and then store it away and use it, you just - pick up as much as you can with your - fingers, and use it for a - with a pint of milk, and then you strain it, and it makes a lovely pudding.</subject2>
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Did you cook the dulce?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 No, no, we - we - we ate the dulce raw. Yes, you could just - carry a - a - a handful about with you and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 K2  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 
Mrs. F. Yes, and there was another, I don't know if you had it here, but we had it there, at Shawbost - I've just remembered it's slouchen. It was - very crinkly and black - it was go on - on the rocks.</subject2>
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Mr. F. Oh well - yes, yes, I know. Oh not - not - not in my day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 K2  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Mrs. F. And they used to - I remember it, and I think it was looked upon as a delicacy. I remember - som
ebody had given my mother some of it and I remember being as a little girl - and - an uncle of mine was at home on holiday from Glasgow and my mother had it, she was boiling it in a pot, and it was getting so thick that she had to add a little water, and 
s
everal people came in and they were teasing her, telling her that she was adding the water to have enough to give - everybody, it wasn't, because it was just getting thick. I don't know what you call it in English, but - it was a black - sort of seaweed. 
B
ut we were very very fond of - of - little - another thing we were very fond of too was catching little crabs, tiny little ones in their holes. And - the - the shell fishes we got. Now they had - they - have cockles here, we don't have them. They used to 
- eat the cockles.</subject2>
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 
Mr. F. Yes, and - and - it's right opposite the house on the sand here. But - I think they're - they're almost - extinct in the - in this island here.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 K2  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Mrs. F. They're not as plentiful as they were. They're lovely, h
ave you ever tasted them? We boil them and sometimes fry them in butter and they're lovely.</subject2>
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Mr. F. I think the - the - the -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 K2  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Mrs. F. Are we mixing you up by having - they were of course much better off being in a farm than we were in
 those days, they had their own sheep again. Now it was the same with - most people, all the crofters, they had a few sheep.</subject2>
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Mr. F. Oh like all the - all the crofters here had - had their own sheep - and cattle. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 So that's one reason why you had more meat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 K2  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Mrs. F. Well with us you see my father didn't have sheep, because he - hadn't the time to look after them.</subject2>
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 And you had salted meat and smoked meat.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Did you ever have any tinned foods?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 
No, I don't think so. I - I - I can't remember having - any tinned stuff at all. We had - we had plenty of our own stuff. It wasn't - it wasn't - ne - necessary to have any - to store any tinned stuff.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 How did you manage for clothes, did your mother make them or was there a dressmaker or a tailor or did you buy them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Yes - oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 You would buy them in Stornaway?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 And they were mended in the home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Yes. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 There wasn't a dressmaker who came round?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 No, not -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Your father was very good at making the boys trousers wasn't he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Yes. Yes. Yes, some men were. Mother - mother - my mother used to - to manufacture - a web of tweed. Yes, yes, I remember it well.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Just for the family would that be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Yes, and sometimes - selling it. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 K2  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Mrs. F. Yes, I think that was done all over.</subject2>
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Mr. F. Yes, all over. That was - that was - when I remember first - that was - a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid10364004\charrsid11559355 d}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 ay - the - the favourite industry here. Because - even - even right here - there was a - a depot.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 K2  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 
Mrs. F. The lady who had this farm - she had a depot here for - and the people used to bring the tweed. The home industry people.</subject2>
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Mr. F. Yes. Yes. Yes. I meant home industry. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 K2  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Mrs. F. And she was of course a great help to the - to the - people, to the poor people.</subject2>
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Mr. F. Oh yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 K2  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Mrs. F. Because - she had a shop here and she supplied them with all that they required.</subject2>
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Mr. F. Now - but most -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 K2  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Mrs. F. This seemed to be a great centre in those days although it's very quiet today.</subject2>
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Do you mean it was a sort of general stores?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Yes. Yes. It used to be -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 When you say the lady, you mean the farmhouse?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Yes, farmhouse - the -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 K3  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 
Mrs. M. The tenant of the farmhouse was a widowed lady, had her husband been alive he would probably have managed the farm, but as she was a widow she had to employ my grandfather to mind the farm for her. And she ran the
 domestic side of it. And the commercial side of it you see.</subject3>
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 It's rather an unusual arrangement.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 K3  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Mrs. M. It is, yes.</subject3>
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Mr. F. Well -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 K2  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Mrs. F. Oh well, she was really a great help to people of this place. They still talk about her.</subject2>
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Mr. F. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 K3  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Mrs. M. There was a family, they were related - a family connection. It was your father and Mrs Macleod were cousins.</subject3>
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Mr. F. Yes, yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 K3  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Mrs. M. That's why you were here.</subject3>
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Mr. F. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 K3  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Mrs. M. She probably wouldn't have employed an outsider.</subject3>
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 K2  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Mrs. F. He - he came from the mainland, from Loch Anne district.</subject2>
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Your father came?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 What was he doing before he came here, what work did he do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Farming. Farming all the days of his life.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Did he ever have his own farm?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 K3  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Mrs. M. Well more or less here, it - he wasn't - it was - he was the farmer here really wasn't he?</subject3>
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Mr. F. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 K3  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Mrs. M. Mrs Macleod had nothing to do with the actual farming work.</subject3>
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Mr. F. No, nothing - nothing - nothing to do with it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 K3  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Mrs. M. Nothing at all.</subject3>
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 K2  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Mrs. F. He really managed the place.</subject2>
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Mr. F. Yes. Yes, he was - guide, philosopher and friend. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 To you you mean?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 K3  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Mrs. M. To her.</subject3>
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Mr. F. No - to - to her. Yes. She - she was a - a widow. Yes. With - three of a family. Yes. And - she relied and depended on my father,
 and so she could. Well she was - she was - she was in - more or less in business. This - this tweed business was - was keeping her occupied. Now - there used to be a - a monthly sailing from Glasgow here, with a - with meal and pro - provisions to the - 
m
ostly to the - to the merchants here. Well - I remember - seven and - up to ten - ton - tons of - of meat be - being stored here, flour and oatmeal. Now - when - the crofters were crofters wives, or both, handed in their tweeds, they used to - to take - s
ometimes - four - four bowls of meal. Along with - along with - the - the various other com - commodities they - they - they required. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 K3  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Mrs. M. They weren't paid in money. They were paid for their tweed in kind.</subject3>
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Mr. F. They - they
 were - they were paid a little. The first thing - the first item on the - on the tweed was put on the counter, the - the weavers wages were taken out. Usually about a pound. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 K2  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Mrs. F. And then all that they required and what was left over they would get the money.</subject2>
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 
Mr. F. Oh - yes. Because - well - in those days, there - there was - large families. Well - especially - when winter was approaching - to - to - provide food for you, perhaps was for three or four sturdy boys. Tackety boots for - for going to sch}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10364004\charrsid11559355 ool in but perhaps for - for ki}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 
cking each other with. Now - and - the best of it was - if a - she used to supply the - the wool to them. They used to - from the sheep}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10364004\charrsid11559355 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 s back - it was all done by hand. Now - I think - I think 
- if I can remember well - a - a stone of wool was twenty-four pounds. Now I think - two stones would make a - fairly sized web of tweed. Now - she would - that - that was - the - the farm wool. Now they were getting that - if I can - say so, dirt cheap. 
Yes. Just to - to enable them to carry on. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 
Could I ask you about discipline in the family, as a child if you did something which your parents disapproved of what would they do about it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Well in our family - I don't think we - as far as I kno
w we deserved more than a - a reprimand. Because - excuse me - we were mostly - we were mostly to ourselves here. So that - we - we weren't really boi - boisterous. Like you - say like you - when there's a - crowd of children together perhaps, they're mor
e boisterous. Yes. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 In bringing you up what did your parents emphasise as important in life?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 
Well - as a child, it was instilled - into us - that - the basic facts, to be honest, truthful, just to be good citizens and to grow up like that. And - the severest reprimand if we told a lie. Yes. As - every child can at certain times. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 If you had worries about something would you keep it to yourself or would you go and talk to your mother or your father about it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Oh yes. Oh yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 You'd talk to them about it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Yes, there was that in - intimacy between - parent and child, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Would you say that you learnt how to behave and so on from both parents or from one rather than the other?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Oh from both. Yes. From both. 
And - the - if we happened to use - any bad words - I believe that - we would get punished for that. There was - there was no excuse for that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Were you allowed to talk when grown ups were talking?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Oh yes. Oh yes, yes. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 K3  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Mrs. M. You weren't allowed to interrupt grown ups.</subject3>
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 
Oh no, no. No, not - not interrupt. No, no. But - as a matter of fact we were encouraged - to - to talk among ourselves, about our lessons, about - what - everyday happenings and all that sort of thing. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 They took an interest in your schoolwork?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Yes. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Were your parents keen on reading?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Yes. Oh yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 So there were quite a few books in the house when you were a boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Yes. And - my father us - always got the newspapers. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Which newspaper was that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 The Scotsman. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 He had it sent over then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 It must have been quite old by the time it got here?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 No. Not at all - well - well - the postal service was quite good. I remember - the post running every second day. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Would other people come here to read his paper?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 No, I - there - there was a - a few people coming into the - into the whole of the district. Yes, oh yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Do you remember having - being taken out by yourself with your father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 What exactly?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Would he take you out, you said you went working with him, but would he take you to Stornaway or something like that, some kind of outing?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Well - whether - Stornaway was so far away from h
ere, it was too - really - really too - out of the question for a - for an outing. Yes, oh yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Would you be taken by your parents visiting, relatives or neighbours?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Oh yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Did they have the caeligs round here?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Yes. Oh yes, in the - in the - in the villages where -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14184279 K3  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Mrs. M. A caeiligs a very much abused term. Yes. A caelig here - a caelig here would mean story telling.</subject3>
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8197677 KF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9644372\charrsid11559355 Mr. F. Oh yes. Yes.
